1 AN ACT
2 RELATING TO CAPITAL EXPENDITURES; AUTHORIZING THE ISSUANCE OF
3 SEVERANCE TAX BONDS; MAKING APPROPRIATIONS FROM THE GENERAL
4 FUND AND OTHER STATE FUNDS; ESTABLISHING CONDITIONS FOR THE
5 ISSUANCE OF SEVERANCE TAX BONDS AND THE EXPENDITURE OF
6 SEVERANCE TAX BOND PROCEEDS; REQUIRING CERTIFICATIONS TO THE
7 DEPARTMENT OF FINANCE AND ADMINISTRATION; ESTABLISHING
8 CONDITIONS FOR THE REVERSION OF UNEXPENDED BALANCES;
9 AUTHORIZING THE ISSUANCE OF SUPPLEMENTAL SEVERANCE TAX BONDS
10 FOR A NEW UNIVERSITY OF NEW MEXICO SCHOOL OF MEDICINE;
11 REQUIRING SUFFICIENT FUNDING FOR TRIBAL INFRASTRUCTURE FUND
12 PROJECTS; MAKING APPROPRIATIONS; DECLARING AN EMERGENCY.
13
14 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF THE STATE OF NEW MEXICO:
15 SECTION 1. SEVERANCE TAX BONDS--AUTHORIZATIONS--
16 APPROPRIATION OF PROCEEDS.--
17 A. The state board of finance may issue and sell
18 severance tax bonds in compliance with the Severance Tax
19 Bonding Act in an amount not to exceed the total of the
20 amounts authorized for purposes specified in this act. The
21 state board of finance shall schedule the issuance and sale
22 of the bonds in the most expeditious and economical manner
23 possible upon a finding by the board that the project has
24 been developed sufficiently to justify the issuance and that
25 the project can proceed to contract within a reasonable time. SFC/SB 240
Page 1

1 The state board of finance shall further take the appropriate
2 steps necessary to comply with the federal Internal Revenue
3 Code of 1986, as amended. Proceeds from the sale of the
4 bonds are appropriated for the purposes specified in this
5 act.
6 B. The agencies named in this act shall certify to
7 the state board of finance when the money from the proceeds
8 of the severance tax bonds appropriated in this section is
9 needed for the purposes specified in the applicable section
10 of this act. If an agency has not certified the need for
11 severance tax bond proceeds for a particular project by the
12 end of fiscal year 2028, the authorization for that project
13 is void.
14 C. Before an agency may certify for the need of
15 severance tax bond proceeds, the project must be developed
16 sufficiently so that the agency reasonably expects to:
(1) incur within six months after the
17
applicable bond proceeds are available for the project a
18
substantial binding obligation to a third party to expend at
19
least five percent of the bond proceeds for the project; and
20
(2) spend at least eighty-five percent of
21
the bond proceeds within three years after the applicable
22
bond proceeds are available for the project.
23
D. Except as otherwise specifically provided by
24
law:
25 SFC/SB 240
Page 2

1 (1) the unexpended balance from the proceeds
2 of severance tax bonds appropriated in this act for a project
3 shall revert to the severance tax bonding fund no later than
4 the following dates:
5 (a) for a project for which severance
6 tax bond proceeds were appropriated to match federal grants,
7 six months after completion of the project;
8 (b) for a project for which severance
9 tax bond proceeds were appropriated to purchase vehicles,
10 including emergency vehicles and other vehicles that require
11 special equipment; heavy equipment; books; educational
12 technology; or other equipment or furniture that is not
13 related to a more inclusive construction or renovation
14 project, at the end of the fiscal year two years following
15 the fiscal year in which the severance tax bond proceeds were
16 made available for the purchase; and
(c) for any other project for which
17
severance tax bonds were appropriated, within six months of
18
completion of the project, but no later than the end of
19
fiscal year 2030; and
20
(2) all remaining balances from the proceeds
21
of severance tax bonds appropriated for a project in this act
22
shall revert to the severance tax bonding fund three months
23
after the latest reversion date specified for that type of
24
project in Paragraph (1) of this subsection.
25 SFC/SB 240
Page 3

1 E. Except for appropriations to the capital
2 program fund, money from severance tax bond proceeds provided
3 pursuant to this act shall not be used to pay indirect
4 project costs.
5 F. Except for a project that was originally funded
6 using a tax-exempt loan or bond issue, a project involving
7 repayment of debt previously incurred shall be funded through
8 the issuance of taxable severance tax bonds with a term that
9 does not extend beyond the fiscal year in which they are
10 issued.
11 G. Money that is appropriated from the proceeds of
12 severance tax bonds pursuant to this act shall not be subject
13 to a binding written agreement with a third party prior to
14 the authorized state agency's approval to enter into that
15 agreement.
16 H. For the purposes of this section, "unexpended
balance" means the remainder of an appropriation after
17
reserving for unpaid costs and expenses subject to a binding
18
written agreement with a third party.
19
SECTION 2. GENERAL FUND APPROPRIATIONS--LIMITATIONS--
20
REVERSIONS.--
21
A. Except as otherwise specifically provided by
22
law, the general fund appropriations made pursuant to this
23
act may be expended in fiscal years 2027 through 2030;
24
provided that the unexpended balance of an appropriation made
25 SFC/SB 240
Page 4

1 in this act from the general fund shall revert to the general
2 fund:
3 (1) no later than September 30 following:
4 (a) the end of fiscal year 2028 for a
5 project for which an appropriation was made to purchase
6 vehicles, including emergency vehicles and other vehicles
7 that require special equipment; heavy equipment; books;
8 educational technology; or other equipment or furniture that
9 is not related to a more inclusive construction or renovation
10 project; or
11 (b) the end of fiscal year 2030 for a
12 project for which an appropriation was made related to an
13 inclusive construction or renovation project; or
14 (2) within six months of completion of the
15 project for any other project for which an appropriation was
16 made, but no later than the end of fiscal year 2030.
B. The agencies named in this act shall certify to
17
the department of finance and administration that the money
18
appropriated in this act is needed for the purposes specified
19
in the applicable section of this act. If an agency has not
20
certified the need for the appropriation for a particular
21
project by the end of fiscal year 2028, the authorization for
22
that project is void.
23
C. Money that is appropriated from the general
24
fund pursuant to this act shall not be subject to a binding
25 SFC/SB 240
Page 5

1 written agreement with a third party prior to the authorized
2 state agency's approval to enter into that agreement.
3 D. For the purposes of this section, "unexpended
4 balance" means the remainder of an appropriation after
5 reserving for unpaid costs and expenses subject to a binding
6 written agreement with a third party.
7 SECTION 3. FUND APPROPRIATIONS OTHER THAN GENERAL
8 FUND--LIMITATIONS--REVERSIONS.--
9 A. Except as otherwise specifically provided by
10 law, the appropriations made pursuant to this act from funds
11 other than the general fund may be expended in fiscal years
12 2027 through 2030; provided that:
13 (1) the unexpended balance of an
14 appropriation made in this act from a fund other than the
15 general fund shall revert to the originating fund no later
16 than the following dates:
(a) for a project for which an
17
appropriation was made to match federal grants, six months
18
after completion of the project;
19
(b) for a project for which an
20
appropriation was made to purchase vehicles, including
21
emergency vehicles and other vehicles that require special
22
equipment; heavy equipment; books; educational technology; or
23
other equipment or furniture that is not related to a more
24
inclusive construction or renovation project, at the end of
25 SFC/SB 240
Page 6

1 the fiscal year two years following the fiscal year in which
2 the appropriation was made for the purchase; and
3 (c) for any other project for which an
4 appropriation was made, within six months of completion of
5 the project, but no later than the end of fiscal year 2030;
6 and
7 (2) all remaining balances from an
8 appropriation made in this act for a project shall revert
9 three months after the latest reversion date specified for
10 that type of project in Paragraph (1) of this subsection.
11 B. Except for appropriations to the capital
12 program fund, money from appropriations made in this act
13 shall not be used to pay indirect project costs.
14 C. Money that is appropriated from a fund other
15 than the general fund pursuant to this act shall not be
16 subject to a binding written agreement with a third party
prior to the authorized state agency's approval to enter into
17
that agreement.
18
D. For the purposes of this section, "unexpended
19
balance" means the remainder of an appropriation after
